<Author>maui50
<Content>Pleasant surprise - could have been a lot worse Trying to book even a few weeks in advance to stay in Berlin on a German bank holiday weekend proved difficult. The more interesting looking and recommended hotels on this site had long been booked up for this popular weekend so we took our chances with City Pension, and didn't expect much. A taxi from Tegel airport at around 11pm cost a mere EUR12 - the hotel was luckily on that side of the city (a fluke!). First impressions at that time of night - dodgy area (lots of seedy bars etc) but no evidence of weirdos on the street. The hotel itself looks dodgy from the outside and inside, the reception area looks quite rough. But the room really made up for these first impressions. Room was huge - large, high-ceilinged and at least three times the size of the average hotel room in any other European capital I've stayed in! The Charlottenburg S-bahn stop (above ground) is just across from the hotel but it was noiseless. The whole room was very clean and functional. The bathroom was on one side of the room but had only a sliding door seperating it from the bedroom - not ideal but you can live with it. Bathroom was clean but very dated and falling apart in places, as was the rest of the hotel. Again, for a cheap room, you can live with this.Breakfast was fine - standard fare in a German hotel - as good it gets anywhere really. The hotel is situated about a minute away from a U-bahn stop in one direcdtion and a minute away from the S-bahn stop in the other direction. Charlottenburg S-bahn will take you direct into the heart of Berlin in 10-15 minutes e.g. Hauptbahnhof, Hackescher Markt etc. This convenience was the hotel's true mark.Would not stay here again if I can help it (would rather stay in Mitte next time - closer to the action) but nonetheless, I was pleasantly surprised and I know it could have been a lot lot worse. Not a bad choice if you're stuck. 
