<Author>rp_aust
<Content>Basic but adequate, managed well Stayed at City Pension for 4 nights in May 2005 with my wife and girl in a triple room for 99 Euro/night. The Pension website makes clear that some rooms have a toilet and some don't. This was also made clear in the email that was sent to me by City Pension. We took a room with a toilet, and looking at the toilets along the hall, I'm glad we did..........The room we had was spacious, with very high ceilings with 19th century ceiling rose and cornices. There was an alcove jutting out into the street which fitted the third bed so that the floor area was not cramped. A small bathroom was built into a box in the inside corner - very small and basic with sliding door that just maintained a deal of privacy. The bathroom was adequate and cleaned OK each day, but cramped and the heat of the hot water went up and down like a yo-yo.City Pension is clearly used by a lot of Germans visiting Berlin for 1-2 nights. Breakfast was nice, continental of course, with fresh rolls.As we were on the next floor up from the reception area/breakfast area, noise was not an issue for us, but we did note that there was a large internal door between the breakfast area (which can be used as a bar at night) and the bedrooms. This would keep any nighttime noise away from the bedrooms - nice.We liked the TV in the room as it was a normal set (not a hotel special), which meant that it had AV inputs and we could connect up our portable DVD player.Berlin itself is not a particularly attractive city, but well worth visiting for things like the bust of Nefetiti, and the Permagon Museum. Also, take enough time to explore KaDeWe - what a Department store should be.We were on a touring holiday and thus needed to park our car. Street parking in the area is available, and the City Pension can provide (at 5 Euro/night) a card to put on the dashboard entitling the car to park in the street outside. The only problem is finding a free spot - we were lucky in that someone pulled out just as we arrived.The location of City Pension is very convenient, being close to both U-Bahn and S-Bahn stations.City Pension is one of those places that could be an absolute horror, but is saved by the care and attention lavished on it by the managers (owners?). If in Berlin again we would certainly consider the City Pension again, but would also look at other places to perhaps get a different aspect to the city. 
